				<div>
					
					
				</div>
				<div> <a href="#" onclick="return imwindow('aim', '263', 400, 200)"><img src="images/misc/im_aim.gif" alt="Send a message via AIM to ClaudShatterglass" border="0" /></a>  </div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Haha, you know something?  I seriously think a prismatic nuke isn't far down the line.<br />
<br />
And you know something?  When wizards finally get it, it's going to have an efficiency that's poor enough to make up for the fact that it gets resisted far less. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smilie" class="inlineimg" />  A lot of people- not all of them, but most is a fair statement- who come up with these &quot;new spell ideas&quot; are merely camoflauging a desire to get their character more power, rather than having a genuine interest in the future of their class.<br />
<br />
You can see this in so many of the posts.  They extoll how good the idea is, how it'll bring ___________ to the wizard class, but they avoid directly stating obvious conclusions like &quot;if a spell is getting resisted thirty percent less, then there's a drastic gain in power to counter that.&quot;  It's almost as if some people hope to &quot;sneak&quot; an idea giving their characters a great deal more power past the developers.<br />
<br />
When that prismatic nuke comes around, people are going to get it expecting that they're going to mem it and once and for all not have to worry about what nuke hits what and what resist goes where, and they're going to see a nuke with a craptacular efficiency and be extremely disappointed.  Mark my words.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
